  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several key ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Standards\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- These establish global standards and expectations for anti-money laundering (AML) practices\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries collaborate on investigating and prosecuting money laundering\n- Sharing of financial intelligence\n- Cross-border legal cooperation mechanisms\n\n3. Regulatory Compliance Requirements\n- Banks and financial institutions must implement AML protocols\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Reporting suspicious transactions\n- These are often implemented through national legislation based on international standards\n\n4. Jurisdictional Coordination\n- Tracking complex financial transactions across borders\n- Extradition agreements\n- Coordinated legal strategies to combat international financial crimes\n\n5. Sanctions and Enforcement\n- International economic sanctions\n- Asset freezing mechanisms\n- Coordinated legal actions against money laundering networks\n\n6. Technology and Information Sharing\n- Digital platforms for financial intelligence exchange\n- Technological tools for tracking transnational financial movements\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multilayered approach to preventing money laundering globally.",
